Quoting dave@llondel.demon.co.uk in article <748837155snx@llondel.demon.co.uk>:
>Easiest way to break a one-time pad is to bribe someone who has access to
>it. Next easiest is probably to steal a copy........ The same goes for a lot
>of security measures: the weakest link can often be a human one.

No, easiest way is to intercept the supposedly secure key channel. 
That's why public-key is in practice more secure than OTP because it
doesn't have such large weak links.  Cryptographically perfect;
practically almost useless.
